{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14096"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14096"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.01,0.04,0.87]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110661"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6764"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92908"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"2310"},{"type":"tags","id":"2897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41697"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110661"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Renal outpatient clinic with worsening itch and nausea over the past few weeks. She has end-stage kidney disease, with had an arteriovenous fistula created two months ago in preparation for commencing haemodialysis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe renal registrar considers whether it would now be appropriate to initiate haemodialysis, but knows that it may not adequately treat all symptoms of chronic kidney disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following kidney functions is not corrected by dialysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluid balance","Phosphate removal","Acid-base balance","Urea removal","Erythropoiesis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDialysis is a life-preserving management option for patients with end-stage kidney disease, replacing many of the essential functions of the kidneys. However, it does not replicate all aspects of kidney function, particularly the endocrine functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythropoiesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the process of red blood cell production, which is stimulated by the hormone erythropoietin. This hormone is primarily produced by the kidneys in response to hypoxia. In end-stage kidney disease, erythropoietin production is significantly reduced, leading to anaemia. Dialysis does not replace this endocrine function, and patients often require exogenous erythropoietin supplementation. It is interesting to note that patients who have their dialysis regimen optimised tend to require less exogenous erythropoietin than those are less adherent with dialysis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid balance\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the primary functions of the kidney corrected by dialysis. The process removes excess fluid from the body, helping to manage fluid overload. Dialysis can be adjusted to remove more or less fluid as needed. Along with dialysis, salt and fluid restrictions are key. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphate removal\u003C/strong\u003E is another important function of dialysis. Hyperphosphataemia is common in end-stage kidney disease and can contribute to vascular calcification. Dialysis helps to remove excess phosphate from the blood. Phosphate binders such as calcium carbonate and sevelamer can help augment phosphate removal in addition to dialysis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcid-base balance\u003C/strong\u003E is maintained by the kidneys in health, and this function is partially replaced by dialysis. The process helps to remove excess acids from the blood, correcting metabolic acidosis that occurs in end-stage kidney disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrea removal\u003C/strong\u003E is a crucial function of dialysis. Urea, a waste product of protein metabolism, accumulates in end-stage kidney disease and contributes to symptoms such as nausea and vomiting. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while dialysis is effective at correcting fluid balance, removing waste products like urea and phosphate, and helping to maintain acid-base balance, it does not replace the endocrine functions of the kidney such as erythropoiesis and vitamin D activation. This highlights the complexity of kidney function and the ongoing challenges in fully replicating all aspects of kidney function in end-stage kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dialysis corrects fluid balance, electrolyte imbalances, and removes waste products, but does not replace endocrine functions of the kidney such as erythropoietin production."],"references":["Johnson RJ, Feehally J. Comprehensive clinical nephrology /. St. Louis: Saunders/Elsevier; 2010."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92908"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14096"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92908"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T19:47:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T19:47:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6764"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110661"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"e